# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genetic-circuits
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A **gene** (or **genetic**) **regulatory network** (**GRN**) is a collection of molecular regulators that interact with each other and with other substances in the cell to govern the gene expression levels of mRNA and proteins which, in turn, determine the function of the cell.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] GRNs also play a central role in morphogenesis, the creation of body structures, which is central to evolutionary developmental biology (evo-devo).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The regulator can be DNA, RNA, protein or any combination of two or more of these three that form a complex, such as a specific sequence of DNA and a transcription factor to activate that sequence.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The interaction can be direct or indirect (through transcribed RNA or translated protein).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In general, each mRNA molecule goes on to make a specific protein (or set of proteins).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In some cases this protein will be structural, and will accumulate at the cell membrane or within the cell to give it particular structural properties.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In other cases the protein will be an enzyme, i.e., a micro-machine that catalyses a certain reaction, such as the breakdown of a food source or toxin.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Some proteins serve only to activate other genes, though, and these are the transcription factors that are the main actors in regulatory networks or cascades.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] By binding to the promoter region at the start of other genes they turn them on, initiating the production of another protein, and so on.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Some transcription factors are inhibitory.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In single-celled organisms, regulatory networks respond to the external environment, optimising the cell at a given time for survival in this environment.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Thus a yeast cell in a sugar solution will turn on genes to make enzymes that process the sugar to alcohol.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This process, which we associate with wine-making, is how the yeast cell makes its living, gaining energy to multiply, which under normal circumstances would enhance its survival prospects.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In multicellular animals the same principle has been put in the service of gene cascades that control body-shape.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Each time a cell divides, two cells result which, although they contain the same genome in full, can differ in which genes are turned on and making proteins.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Sometimes a 'self-sustaining feedback loop' ensures that a cell maintains its identity and passes it on.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Less understood is the mechanism of epigenetics by which chromatin modification may provide cellular memory by blocking or allowing transcription.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A major feature of multicellular animals is the use of morphogen gradients, which in effect provide a positioning system that tells a cell where in the body it is, and hence what sort of cell to become.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A gene that is turned on in one cell may make a product that leaves the cell and diffuses through adjacent cells, entering them and turning on genes only when it is present above a certain threshold level.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] These cells are thus induced into a new fate, and may even generate other morphogens that signal back to the original cell.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Over longer distances morphogens may use the active process of signal transduction.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Such signalling controls embryogenesis, the building of a body plan from scratch through a series of sequential steps.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] They also control and maintain adult bodies through feedback processes, and the loss of such feedback because of a mutation can be responsible for the cell proliferation that is seen in cancer.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In parallel with this process of building structure, the gene cascade turns on genes that make structural proteins that give each cell the physical properties it needs.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] At one level, biological cells can be thought of as "partially mixed bags" of biological chemicals – in the discussion of gene regulatory networks, these chemicals are mostly the messenger RNAs (mRNAs) and proteins that arise from gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] These mRNA and proteins interact with each other with various degrees of specificity.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Others are bound to cell membranes, interacting with molecules in the environment.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Still others pass through cell membranes and mediate long range signals to other cells in a multi-cellular organism.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] These molecules and their interactions comprise a *gene regulatory network*.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The nodes of this network can represent genes, proteins, mRNAs, protein/protein complexes or cellular processes.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Nodes that are depicted as lying along vertical lines are associated with the cell/environment interfaces, while the others are free-floating and can diffuse.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The nodes can regulate themselves directly or indirectly, creating feedback loops, which form cyclic chains of dependencies in the topological network.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The network structure is an abstraction of the system's molecular or chemical dynamics, describing the manifold ways in which one substance affects all the others to which it is connected.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In practice, such GRNs are inferred from the biological literature on a given system and represent a distillation of the collective knowledge about a set of related biochemical reactions.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] To speed up the manual curation of GRNs, some recent efforts try to use text mining, curated databases, network inference from massive data, model checking and other information extraction technologies for this purpose.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Genes can be viewed as nodes in the network, with input being proteins such as transcription factors, and outputs being the level of gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The value of the node depends on a function which depends on the value of its regulators in previous time steps (in the Boolean network described below these are Boolean functions, typically AND, OR, and NOT).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] These functions have been interpreted as performing a kind of information processing within the cell, which determines cellular behavior.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The basic drivers within cells are concentrations of some proteins, which determine both spatial (location within the cell or tissue) and temporal (cell cycle or developmental stage) coordinates of the cell, as a kind of "cellular memory".
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The gene networks are only beginning to be understood, and it is a next step for biology to attempt to deduce the functions for each gene "node", to help understand the behavior of the system in increasing levels of complexity, from gene to signaling pathway, cell or tissue level.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Mathematical models of GRNs have been developed to capture the behavior of the system being modeled, and in some cases generate predictions corresponding with experimental observations.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In some other cases, models have proven to make accurate novel predictions, which can be tested experimentally, thus suggesting new approaches to explore in an experiment that sometimes wouldn't be considered in the design of the protocol of an experimental laboratory.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Modeling techniques include differential equations (ODEs), Boolean networks, Petri nets, Bayesian networks, graphical Gaussian network models, Stochastic, and Process Calculi.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Conversely, techniques have been proposed for generating models of GRNs that best explain a set of time series observations.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Recently it has been shown that ChIP-seq signal of histone modification are more correlated with transcription factor motifs at promoters in comparison to RNA level.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Hence it is proposed that time-series histone modification ChIP-seq could provide more reliable inference of gene-regulatory networks in comparison to methods based on expression levels.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Gene regulatory networks are generally thought to be made up of a few highly connected nodes (hubs) and many poorly connected nodes nested within a hierarchical regulatory regime.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Thus gene regulatory networks approximate a hierarchical scale free network topology.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This is consistent with the view that most genes have limited pleiotropy and operate within regulatory modules.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This structure is thought to evolve due to the preferential attachment of duplicated genes to more highly connected genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Recent work has also shown that natural selection tends to favor networks with sparse connectivity.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] There are primarily two ways that networks can evolve, both of which can occur simultaneously.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The first is that network topology can be changed by the addition or subtraction of nodes (genes) or parts of the network (modules) may be expressed in different contexts.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The*Drosophila* Hippo signaling pathway provides a good example.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The Hippo signaling pathway controls both mitotic growth and post-mitotic cellular differentiation.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Recently it was found that the network the Hippo signaling pathway operates in differs between these two functions which in turn changes the behavior of the Hippo signaling pathway.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This suggests that the Hippo signaling pathway operates as a conserved regulatory module that can be used for multiple functions depending on context.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Thus, changing network topology can allow a conserved module to serve multiple functions and alter the final output of the network.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The second way networks can evolve is by changing the strength of interactions between nodes, such as how strongly a transcription factor may bind to a cis-regulatory element.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Such variation in strength of network edges has been shown to underlie between species variation in vulva cell fate patterning of *Caenorhabditis* worms.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Another characteristic of gene regulatory network is their abundance of certain repetitive sub-networks known as network motifs.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Network motifs can be regarded as repetitive topological patterns when dividing a big network into small blocks.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Several types of motifs appear more often in gene regulatory networks than in randomly generated networks.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] As an example, one such motif is called feed-forward loops, which consist of three nodes.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This motif is the most abundant among all possible motifs made up of three nodes, as is shown in the gene regulatory networks of fly, nematode, and human.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The enriched motifs have been proposed to follow convergent evolution, suggesting they are "optimal designs" for certain regulatory purposes.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] For example, modeling shows that feed-forward loops are able to coordinate the change in node A (in terms of concentration and activity) and the expression dynamics of node C, creating different input-output behaviors.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The galactose utilization system of *E. coli* contains a feed-forward loop which accelerates the activation of galactose utilization operon *galETK*, potentially facilitating the metabolic transition to galactose when glucose is depleted.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The feed-forward loop in the arabinose utilization systems of *E.coli* delays the activation of arabinose catabolism operon and transporters, potentially avoiding unnecessary metabolic transition due to temporary fluctuations in upstream signaling pathways.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Similarly in the Wnt signaling pathway of *Xenopus*, the feed-forward loop acts as a fold-change detector that responses to the fold change, rather than the absolute change, in the level of β-catenin, potentially increasing the resistance to fluctuations in β-catenin levels.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Following the convergent evolution hypothesis, the enrichment of feed-forward loops would be an adaptation for fast response and noise resistance.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A recent research found that yeast grown in an environment of constant glucose developed mutations in glucose signaling pathways and growth regulation pathway, suggesting regulatory components responding to environmental changes are dispensable under constant environment.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] On the other hand, some researchers hypothesize that the enrichment of network motifs is non-adaptive.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In other words, gene regulatory networks can evolve to a similar structure without the specific selection on the proposed input-output behavior.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Support for this hypothesis often comes from computational simulations.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] For example, fluctuations in the abundance of feed-forward loops in a model that simulates the evolution of gene regulatory networks by randomly rewiring nodes may suggest that the enrichment of feed-forward loops is a side-effect of evolution.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In another model of gene regulator networks evolution, the ratio of the frequencies of gene duplication and gene deletion show great influence on network topology: certain ratios lead to the enrichment of feed-forward loops and create networks that show features of hierarchical scale free networks.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A heuristic approach to developing GRNs has the potential to improve understanding of gene regulation by modelling GRNs as small-world networks, in which genes are densely interconnected through a small number of intermediate regulatory steps, enabling rapid signal propagation across the network.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This reveals that GRNs exhibit scale-free topology, characterised by a small number of highly connected hub genes that exert disproportionate regulatory influence over the broader network.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Regulatory networks allow bacteria to adapt to almost every environmental niche on earth.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A network of interactions among diverse types of molecules including DNA, RNA, proteins and metabolites, is utilised by the bacteria to achieve regulation of gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In bacteria, the principal function of regulatory networks is to control the response to environmental changes, for example nutritional status and environmental stress.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A complex organization of networks permits the microorganism to coordinate and integrate multiple environmental signals.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] One example stress is when the environment suddenly becomes poor of nutrients.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This triggers a complex adaptation process in bacteria, such as *E. coli.* After this environmental change, thousands of genes change expression level.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] However, these changes are predictable from the topology and logic of the gene network that is reported in RegulonDB.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Specifically, on average, the response strength of a gene was predictable from the difference between the numbers of activating and repressing input transcription factors of that gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] It is common to model such a network with a set of coupled ordinary differential equations (ODEs) or SDEs, describing the reaction kinetics of the constituent parts.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Suppose that our regulatory network has N nodes, and let $S_{1}(t),S_{2}(t),\ldots ,S_{N}(t)$ represent the concentrations of the N corresponding substances at time t .
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] where the functions $f_{j}$ express the dependence of $S_{j}$ on the concentrations of other substances present in the cell.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The functions $f_{j}$ are ultimately derived from basic principles of chemical kinetics or simple expressions derived from these e.g.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Hence, the functional forms of the $f_{j}$ are usually chosen as low-order polynomials or Hill functions that serve as an ansatz for the real molecular dynamics.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Such models are then studied using the mathematics of nonlinear dynamics.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] System-specific information, like reaction rate constants and sensitivities, are encoded as constant parameters.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] for all j , one obtains (possibly several) concentration profiles of proteins and mRNAs that are theoretically sustainable (though not necessarily stable).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Steady states of kinetic equations thus correspond to potential cell types, and oscillatory solutions to the above equation to naturally cyclic cell types.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Mathematical stability of these attractors can usually be characterized by the sign of higher derivatives at critical points, and then correspond to biochemical stability of the concentration profile.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Critical points and bifurcations in the equations correspond to critical cell states in which small state or parameter perturbations could switch the system between one of several stable differentiation fates.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Trajectories correspond to the unfolding of biological pathways and transients of the equations to short-term biological events.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] For a more mathematical discussion, see the articles on nonlinearity, dynamical systems, bifurcation theory, and chaos theory.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The following example illustrates how a Boolean network can model a GRN together with its gene products (the outputs) and the substances from the environment that affect it (the inputs).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Stuart Kauffman was amongst the first biologists to use the metaphor of Boolean networks to model genetic regulatory networks.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Each node in the graph can be in one of two states: on or off.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] For a gene, "on" corresponds to the gene being expressed; for inputs and outputs, "on" corresponds to the substance being present.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Time is viewed as proceeding in discrete steps.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] At each step, the new state of a node is a Boolean function of the prior states of the nodes with arrows pointing towards it.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The validity of the model can be tested by comparing simulation results with time series observations.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A partial validation of a Boolean network model can also come from testing the predicted existence of a yet unknown regulatory connection between two particular transcription factors that each are nodes of the model.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Continuous network models of GRNs are an extension of the Boolean networks described above.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Nodes still represent genes and connections between them regulatory influences on gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Genes in biological systems display a continuous range of activity levels and it has been argued that using a continuous representation captures several properties of gene regulatory networks not present in the Boolean model.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Formally most of these approaches are similar to an artificial neural network, as inputs to a node are summed up and the result serves as input to a sigmoid function, e.g., but proteins do often control gene expression in a synergistic, i.e. non-linear, way.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] However, there is now a continuous network model that allows grouping of inputs to a node thus realizing another level of regulation.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This model is formally closer to a higher order recurrent neural network.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The same model has also been used to mimic the evolution of cellular differentiation and even multicellular morphogenesis.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Experimental results have demonstrated that gene expression is a stochastic process.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Thus, many authors are now using the stochastic formalism, after the work by Arkin et al.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Works on single gene expression and small synthetic genetic networks, such as the genetic toggle switch of Tim Gardner and Jim Collins, provided additional experimental data on the phenotypic variability and the stochastic nature of gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The first versions of stochastic models of gene expression involved only instantaneous reactions and were driven by the Gillespie algorithm.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] From here, a set of reactions was proposed that allow generating GRNs.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] These are then simulated using a modified version of the Gillespie algorithm, that can simulate multiple time delayed reactions (chemical reactions where each of the products is provided a time delay that determines when will it be released in the system as a "finished product").
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Furthermore, there seems to be a trade-off between the noise in gene expression, the speed with which genes can switch, and the metabolic cost associated their functioning.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] More specifically, for any given level of metabolic cost, there is an optimal trade-off between noise and processing speed and increasing the metabolic cost leads to better speed-noise trade-offs.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] A recent work proposed a simulator (SGNSim, *Stochastic Gene Networks Simulator*), that can model GRNs where transcription and translation are modeled as multiple time delayed events and its dynamics is driven by a stochastic simulation algorithm (SSA) able to deal with multiple time delayed events.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The time delays can be drawn from several distributions and the reaction rates from complex functions or from physical parameters.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] SGNSim can generate ensembles of GRNs within a set of user-defined parameters, such as topology.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] It can also be used to model specific GRNs and systems of chemical reactions.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Genetic perturbations such as gene deletions, gene over-expression, insertions, frame shift mutations can also be modeled as well.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The GRN is created from a graph with the desired topology, imposing in-degree and out-degree distributions.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Gene promoter activities are affected by other genes expression products that act as inputs, in the form of monomers or combined into multimers and set as direct or indirect.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Next, each direct input is assigned to an operator site and different transcription factors can be allowed, or not, to compete for the same operator site, while indirect inputs are given a target.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Finally, a function is assigned to each gene, defining the gene's response to a combination of transcription factors (promoter state).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The transfer functions (that is, how genes respond to a combination of inputs) can be assigned to each combination of promoter states as desired.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] In other recent work, multiscale models of gene regulatory networks have been developed that focus on synthetic biology applications.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Simulations have been used that model all biomolecular interactions in transcription, translation, regulation, and induction of gene regulatory networks, guiding the design of synthetic systems.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Other work has focused on predicting the gene expression levels in a gene regulatory network.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] The approaches used to model gene regulatory networks have been constrained to be interpretable and, as a result, are generally simplified versions of the network.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] For example, Boolean networks have been used due to their simplicity and ability to handle noisy data but lose data information by having a binary representation of the genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Also, artificial neural networks omit using a hidden layer so that they can be interpreted, losing the ability to model higher order correlations in the data.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Using a model that is not constrained to be interpretable, a more accurate model can be produced.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Being able to predict gene expressions more accurately provides a way to explore how drugs affect a system of genes as well as for finding which genes are interrelated in a process.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] This has been encouraged by the DREAM competition which promotes a competition for the best prediction algorithms.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Some other recent work has used artificial neural networks with a hidden layer.
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] There are three classes of multiple sclerosis: relapsing-remitting (RRMS), primary progressive (PPMS) and secondary progressive (SPMS).
[src:genetic-circuits/gene-regulatory-network] Gene regulatory network (GRN) plays a vital role to understand the disease mechanism across these three different multiple sclerosis classes.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] In genetics, an **operon** is a functioning unit of DNA containing a cluster of genes under the control of a single promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The genes are transcribed together into an mRNA strand and either translated together in the cytoplasm, or undergo splicing to create monocistronic mRNAs that are translated separately, i.e. several strands of mRNA that each encode a single gene product.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The result of this is that the genes contained in the operon are either expressed together or not at all.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Several genes must be *co-transcribed* to define an operon.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Originally, operons were thought to exist solely in prokaryotes (which includes organelles like plastids that are derived from bacteria), but their discovery in eukaryotes was shown in the early 1990s, and are considered to be rare.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] In general, expression of prokaryotic operons leads to the generation of polycistronic mRNAs, while eukaryotic operons lead to monocistronic mRNAs.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Operons are also found in viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] For example, T7 phages have two operons.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The first operon codes for various products, including a special T7 RNA polymerase which can bind to and transcribe the second operon.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The second operon includes a lysis gene whose function is to cause the host cell to burst.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The term "operon" was first proposed in a short paper in the Proceedings of the French Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] From this paper, the so-called general theory of the operon was developed.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] This theory suggested that in all cases, genes within an operon are negatively controlled by a repressor acting at a single operator located before the first gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Later, it was discovered that genes could be positively regulated and also regulated at steps that follow transcription initiation.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Therefore, it is not possible to talk of a general regulatory mechanism, because different operons have different mechanisms.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Today, the operon is simply defined as a cluster of genes transcribed into a single mRNA molecule.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Nevertheless, the development of the concept is considered a landmark event in the history of molecular biology.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The first operon to be described was the *lac* operon in *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The 1965 Nobel Prize in Physiology and Medicine was awarded to François Jacob, André Michel Lwoff and Jacques Monod for their discoveries concerning the operon and virus synthesis.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Operons occur primarily in prokaryotes but also rarely in some eukaryotes, including nematodes such as *C. elegans* and the fruit fly, *Drosophila melanogaster*. rRNA genes often exist in operons that have been found in a range of eukaryotes including chordates.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] An operon is made up of several structural genes arranged under a common promoter and regulated by a common operator.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] It is defined as a set of adjacent structural genes, plus the adjacent regulatory signals that affect transcription of the structural genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The regulators of a given operon, including repressors, corepressors, and activators, are not necessarily coded for by that operon.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The location and condition of the regulators, promoter, operator and structural DNA sequences can determine the effects of common mutations.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Operons are related to regulons, stimulons and modulons; whereas operons contain a set of genes regulated by the same operator, regulons contain a set of genes under regulation by a single regulatory protein, and stimulons contain a set of genes under regulation by a single cell stimulus.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] According to its authors, the term "operon" is derived from the verb "to operate".
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] An operon contains one or more structural genes which are generally transcribed into one polycistronic mRNA (a single mRNA molecule that codes for more than one protein).
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] However, the definition of an operon does not require the mRNA to be polycistronic, though in practice, it usually is.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Upstream of the structural genes lies a promoter sequence which provides a site for RNA polymerase to bind and initiate transcription.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Close to the promoter lies a section of DNA called an *operator*.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] All the structural genes of an operon are turned ON or OFF together, due to a single promoter and operator upstream to them, but sometimes more control over the gene expression is needed.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] To achieve this aspect, some bacterial genes are located near together, but there is a specific promoter for each of them; this is called gene clustering.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Usually these genes encode proteins which will work together in the same pathway, such as a metabolic pathway.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Gene clustering helps a prokaryotic cell to produce metabolic enzymes in a correct order.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Not always included within the operon, but important in its function is a regulatory gene, a constantly expressed gene which codes for repressor proteins.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The regulatory gene does not need to be in, adjacent to, or even near the operon to control it.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] An inducer (small molecule) can displace a repressor (protein) from the operator site (DNA), resulting in an uninhibited operon.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Alternatively, a corepressor can bind to the repressor to allow its binding to the operator site.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] A good example of this type of regulation is seen for the trp operon.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Control of an operon is a type of gene regulation that enables organisms to regulate the expression of various genes depending on environmental conditions.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Operon regulation can be either negative or positive by induction or repression.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Negative control involves the binding of a repressor to the operator to prevent transcription.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Operons can also be positively controlled.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] With positive control, an activator protein stimulates transcription by binding to DNA (usually at a site other than the operator).
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The *lac* operon of the model bacterium *Escherichia coli* was the first operon to be discovered and provides a typical example of operon function.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] It consists of three adjacent structural genes, a promoter, a terminator, and an operator.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The *lac* operon is regulated by several factors including the availability of glucose and lactose.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Lactose binds to the repressor protein and prevents it from repressing gene transcription.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] This is an example of the derepressible (from above: negative inducible) model.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] So it is a negative inducible operon induced by presence of lactose or allolactose.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Discovered in 1953 by Jacques Monod and colleagues, the trp operon in *E. coli* was the first repressible operon to be discovered.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] While the lac operon can be activated by a chemical (allolactose), the tryptophan (Trp) operon is inhibited by a chemical (tryptophan).
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] This operon contains five structural genes: trp E, trp D, trp C, trp B, and trp A, which encodes tryptophan synthetase.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] It also contains a promoter which binds to RNA polymerase and an operator which blocks transcription when bound to the protein synthesized by the repressor gene (trp R) that binds to the operator.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] In the lac operon, lactose binds to the repressor protein and prevents it from repressing gene transcription, while in the trp operon, tryptophan binds to the repressor protein and enables it to repress gene transcription.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Also unlike the lac operon, the trp operon contains a leader peptide and an attenuator sequence which allows for graded regulation.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] This is an example of the corepressible model.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The number and organization of operons has been studied most critically in *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] As a result, predictions can be made based on an organism's genomic sequence.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] One prediction method uses the intergenic distance between reading frames as a primary predictor of the number of operons in the genome.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The separation merely changes the frame and guarantees that the read through is efficient.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Longer stretches exist where operons start and stop, often up to 40–50 bases.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] An alternative method to predict operons is based on finding gene clusters where gene order and orientation is conserved in two or more genomes.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Operon prediction is even more accurate if the functional class of the molecules is considered.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Bacteria have clustered their reading frames into units, sequestered by co-involvement in protein complexes, common pathways, or shared substrates and transporters.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Thus, accurate prediction would involve all of these data, a difficult task indeed.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Pascale Cossart's laboratory was the first to experimentally identify all operons of a microorganism, *Listeria monocytogenes*.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] The 517 polycistronic operons are listed in a 2009 study describing the global changes in transcription that occur in *L. monocytogenes* under different conditions.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Primary promoters are the main controllers of operons.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] However, many operons have internal promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] For example, half of all operons of *E. coli* have internal promoters*.* What happens when both the primary as well as the internal promoters are simultaneously perturbed?
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] A recent study followed how each gene in each operon responded to such genome-wide stresses.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] They found that many transcription events of operons end prematurely in those conditions.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] They also found that internal promoters compensate significantly for those terminations creating a wave-like response pattern along operons.
[src:genetic-circuits/operon] Next, it was shown that the same occurs in evolutionarily distant bacteria, such as Bacillus subtilis, Corynebacterium glutamicum, and Helicobacter pylori.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In genetics, a **promoter** is a sequence of DNA to which proteins bind to initiate transcription of a single RNA transcript from the DNA downstream of the promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The RNA transcript may encode a protein (mRNA), or can have a function in and of itself, such as tRNA or rRNA.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Promoters are located near the transcription start sites of genes, upstream on the DNA (towards the 5' region of the sense strand).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Promoters can be about 100–1000 base pairs long, the sequence of which is highly dependent on the gene and product of transcription, type or class of RNA polymerase recruited to the site, and species of organism.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] For transcription to take place, the enzyme that synthesizes RNA, known as RNA polymerase, must attach to the DNA near a gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Promoters contain specific DNA sequences such as response elements that provide a secure initial binding site for RNA polymerase and for proteins called transcription factors that recruit RNA polymerase.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] These transcription factors have specific activator or repressor sequences of corresponding nucleotides that attach to specific promoters and regulate gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The promoter resembles a eukaryotic one, though much more simplified.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] It contains BRE and TATA elements and are recognized by TFB and TBP.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Promoters represent critical elements that can work in concert with other regulatory regions (enhancers, silencers, boundary elements/insulators) to direct the level of transcription of a given gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A promoter is induced in response to changes in abundance or conformation of regulatory proteins in a cell, which enable activating transcription factors to recruit RNA polymerase.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Given the short sequences of most promoter elements, promoters can rapidly evolve from random sequences.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] For instance, in *E. coli*, ~60% of random sequences can evolve expression levels comparable to the wild-type lac promoter with only one mutation, and that ~10% of random sequences can serve as active promoters even without evolution.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In bacteria, the promoter contains two short sequence elements approximately 10 (Pribnow Box) and 35 nucleotides *upstream* from the transcription start site.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The above promoter sequences are recognized only by RNA polymerase holoenzyme containing sigma-70.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] RNA polymerase holoenzymes containing other sigma factors recognize different core promoter sequences.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Promoters can be very closely located in the DNA.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Such "closely spaced promoters" have been observed in the DNAs of all life forms, from humans to prokaryotes and are highly conserved.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Therefore, they may provide some (presently unknown) advantages.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] These pairs of promoters can be positioned in divergent, tandem, and convergent directions.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] They can also be regulated by transcription factors and differ in various features, such as the nucleotide distance between them, the two promoter strengths, etc.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The most important aspect of two closely spaced promoters is that they will, most likely, interfere with each other.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Several studies have explored this using both analytical and stochastic models.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] There are also studies that measured gene expression in synthetic genes or from one to a few genes controlled by bidirectional promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] More recently, one study measured most genes controlled by tandem promoters in *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In that study, two main forms of interference were measured.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] One is when an RNAP is on the downstream promoter, blocking the movement of RNAPs elongating from the upstream promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The other is when the two promoters are so close that when an RNAP sits on one of the promoters, it blocks any other RNAP from reaching the other promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] These events are possible because the RNAP occupies several nucleotides when bound to the DNA, including in transcription start sites.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Similar events occur when the promoters are in divergent and convergent formations.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The possible events also depend on the distance between them.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Gene promoters are typically located upstream of the gene and can have regulatory elements several kilobases away from the transcriptional start site (enhancers).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In eukaryotes, the transcriptional complex can cause the DNA to bend back on itself, which allows for placement of regulatory sequences far from the actual site of transcription.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Eukaryotic RNA-polymerase-II-dependent promoters can contain a TATA box (consensus sequence TATAAA), which is recognized by the general transcription factor TATA-binding protein (TBP); and a B recognition element (BRE), which is recognized by the general transcription factor TFIIB.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The TATA element and BRE typically are located close to the transcriptional start site (typically within 30 to 40 base pairs).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Eukaryotic promoter regulatory sequences typically bind proteins called transcription factors that are involved in the formation of the transcriptional complex.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] An example is the E-box (sequence CACGTG), which binds transcription factors in the basic helix-loop-helix (bHLH) family (e.g.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Some promoters that are targeted by multiple transcription factors might achieve a hyperactive state, leading to increased transcriptional activity.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Up-regulated expression of genes in mammals is initiated when signals are transmitted to the promoters associated with the genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The presence of multiple methylated CpG sites in CpG islands of promoters causes stable silencing of genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] However, the presence or absence of the other elements have relatively small effects on gene expression in experiments.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Two sequences, the TATA box and Inr, caused small but significant increases in expression (45% and 28% increases, respectively).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The BREu and the BREd elements significantly decreased expression by 35% and 20%, respectively, and the DPE element had no detected effect on expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Cis-regulatory modules that are localized in DNA regions distant from the promoters of genes can have very large effects on gene expression, with some genes undergoing up to 100-fold increased expression due to such a cis-regulatory module.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] These cis-regulatory modules include enhancers, silencers, insulators and tethering elements.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Among this constellation of elements, enhancers and their associated transcription factors have a leading role in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Enhancers are regions of the genome that are major gene-regulatory elements.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Enhancers control cell-type-specific gene expression programs, most often by looping through long distances to come in physical proximity with the promoters of their target genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In a study of brain cortical neurons, 24,937 loops were found, bringing enhancers to promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Multiple enhancers, each often at tens or hundred of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and coordinate with each other to control expression of their common target gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The schematic illustration in this section shows an enhancer looping around to come into close physical proximity with the promoter of a target gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The loop is stabilized by a dimer of a connector protein (e.g. dimer of CTCF or YY1), with one member of the dimer anchored to its binding motif on the enhancer and the other member anchored to its binding motif on the promoter (represented by the red zigzags in the illustration).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Mediator (coactivator) (a complex usually consisting of about 26 proteins in an interacting structure) communicates regulatory signals from enhancer DNA-bound transcription factors directly to the RNA polymerase II (pol II) enzyme bound to the promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two eRNAs as illustrated in the Figure.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] An inactive enhancer may be bound by an inactive transcription factor.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Phosphorylation of the transcription factor may activate it and that activated transcription factor may then activate the enhancer to which it is bound (see small red star representing phosphorylation of transcription factor bound to enhancer in the illustration).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] An activated enhancer begins transcription of its RNA before activating a promoter to initiate transcription of messenger RNA from its target gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Bidirectional promoters are short (<1 kbp) intergenic regions of DNA between the 5' ends of the genes in a bidirectional gene pair.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A "bidirectional gene pair" refers to two adjacent genes coded on opposite strands, with their 5' ends oriented toward one another.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The two genes are often functionally related, and modification of their shared promoter region allows them to be co-regulated and thus co-expressed.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Bidirectional promoters are a common feature of mammalian genomes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] About 11% of human genes are bidirectionally paired.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Bidirectionally paired genes in the Gene Ontology database shared at least one database-assigned functional category with their partners 47% of the time.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Microarray analysis has shown bidirectionally paired genes to be co-expressed to a higher degree than random genes or neighboring unidirectional genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Although co-expression does not necessarily indicate co-regulation, methylation of bidirectional promoter regions has been shown to downregulate both genes, and demethylation to upregulate both genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In some cases (about 11%), only one gene of a bidirectional pair is expressed.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In these cases, the promoter is implicated in suppression of the non-expressed gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The mechanism behind this could be competition for the same polymerases, or chromatin modification.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Divergent transcription could shift nucleosomes to upregulate transcription of one gene, or remove bound transcription factors to downregulate transcription of one gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Some functional classes of genes are more likely to be bidirectionally paired than others.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Genes implicated in DNA repair are five times more likely to be regulated by bidirectional promoters than by unidirectional promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Chaperone proteins are three times more likely, and mitochondrial genes are more than twice as likely.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Many basic housekeeping and cellular metabolic genes are regulated by bidirectional promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The overrepresentation of bidirectionally paired DNA repair genes associates these promoters with cancer.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Forty-five percent of human somatic oncogenes seem to be regulated by bidirectional promoters – significantly more than non-cancer causing genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Hypermethylation of the promoters between gene pairs WNT9A/CD558500, CTDSPL/BC040563, and KCNK15/BF195580 has been associated with tumors.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Certain sequence characteristics have been observed in bidirectional promoters, including a lack of TATA boxes, an abundance of CpG islands, and a symmetry around the midpoint of dominant Cs and As on one side and Gs and Ts on the other.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A motif with the consensus sequence of TCTCGCGAGA, also called the CGCG element, was recently shown to drive PolII-driven bidirectional transcription in CpG islands.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] CCAAT boxes are common, as they are in many promoters that lack TATA boxes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In addition, the motifs NRF-1, GABPA, YY1, and ACTACAnnTCCC are represented in bidirectional promoters at significantly higher rates than in unidirectional promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The absence of TATA boxes in bidirectional promoters suggests that TATA boxes play a role in determining the directionality of promoters, but counterexamples of bidirectional promoters do possess TATA boxes and unidirectional promoters without them indicates that they cannot be the only factor.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Although the term "bidirectional promoter" refers specifically to promoter regions of mRNA-encoding genes, luciferase assays have shown that over half of human genes do not have a strong directional bias.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Research suggests that non-coding RNAs are frequently associated with the promoter regions of mRNA-encoding genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] It has been hypothesized that the recruitment and initiation of RNA polymerase II usually begins bidirectionally, but divergent transcription is halted at a checkpoint later during elongation.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Possible mechanisms behind this regulation include sequences in the promoter region, chromatin modification, and the spatial orientation of the DNA.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The archaeal promoter resembles a eukaryotic one: a TATA box (at -26/-27) and an upstream BRE (at -33/-34) are commonly found, binding to TBP and TFB (homolog of TFIIB).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] There are also occasionally an initiator element (INR) near the transcription start site [TSS], and a promoter proximal element (PPE) between BRE-TATA and TSS.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] These two are not necessary, but enhance the strength of a promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] TFE (homolog of TFIIE) promotes initiation at suboptimal promoter sequences.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] It binds between -10 and +1, near the Inr.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Strict conservation of these motifs are not necessary, and many archaea with high GC% show "degenerated" TATA boxes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Rather, it's the energetic (duplex enthalpy, duplex stability) and structural (intrinsic curvature, bendability) features of the promoter that mainly matter.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A subgenomic promoter is a promoter added to a virus for a specific heterologous gene, resulting in the formation of mRNA for that gene alone.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Many positive-sense RNA viruses produce these subgenomic mRNAs (sgRNA) as one of the common infection techniques used by these viruses and generally transcribe late viral genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Subgenomic promoters range from 24 nucleotide (Sindbis virus) to over 100 nucleotides (Beet necrotic yellow vein virus) and are usually found upstream of the transcription start.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A wide variety of algorithms have been developed to facilitate detection of promoters in genomic sequence, and promoter prediction is a common element of many gene prediction methods.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A bacterial promoter region is located before the -35 and -10 Consensus sequences.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The closer the promoter region is to the consensus sequences the more often transcription of that gene will take place.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] There is not a set pattern for promoter regions as there are for consensus sequences.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] One approach is to use a biophysical theory of why promoters work.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] For archaea, a combination of calculated energetic and structural features can detect promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] For bacteria, a biophysical model that estimates RNAP-sigma70 binding probability can detect and estimate the strengths of promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Another approach is to use a pattern-matching program based on known promoters, from simple hand-crafted regular expressions to advanced machine learning methods such as decision trees, hidden Markov models (HMM), and neural networks.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] YAPP, an 2000s eukaryotic core-promoter prediction program, uses HMM.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A 2017 publication predicts bacterial and eukaryotic promoters using a convolutional neural network.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The promoter binding process is crucial in the understanding of the process of gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Tuning synthetic genetic systems relies on precisely engineered synthetic promoters with known levels of transcription rates.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Although RNA polymerase holoenzyme shows high affinity to non-specific sites of the DNA, this characteristic does not allow us to clarify the process of promoter location.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] This process of promoter location has been attributed to the structure of the holoenzyme to DNA and sigma 4 to DNA complexes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Most diseases are heterogeneous in cause, meaning that one "disease" is often many different diseases at the molecular level, though symptoms exhibited and response to treatment may be identical.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] How diseases of different molecular origin respond to treatments is partially addressed in the discipline of pharmacogenomics.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Not listed here are the many kinds of cancers involving aberrant transcriptional regulation owing to creation of chimeric genes through pathological chromosomal translocation.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Importantly, intervention in the number or structure of promoter-bound proteins is one key to treating a disease without affecting expression of unrelated genes sharing elements with the target gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Some genes whose change is not desirable are capable of influencing the potential of a cell to become cancerous.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In humans, about 70% of promoters located near the transcription start site of a gene (proximal promoters) contain a CpG island.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] CpG islands are generally 200 to 2000 base pairs long, have a C:G base pair content >50%, and have regions of DNA where a cytosine nucleotide is followed by a guanine nucleotide and this occurs frequently in the linear sequence of bases along its 5' → 3' direction.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Distal promoters also frequently contain CpG islands, such as the promoter of the DNA repair gene *ERCC1*, where the CpG island-containing promoter is located about 5,400 nucleotides upstream of the coding region of the *ERCC1* gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] CpG islands also occur frequently in promoters for functional noncoding RNAs such as microRNAs.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In humans, DNA methylation occurs at the 5' position of the pyrimidine ring of the cytosine residues within CpG sites to form 5-methylcytosines.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Silencing of a gene may be initiated by other mechanisms, but this is often followed by methylation of CpG sites in the promoter CpG island to cause the stable silencing of the gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Generally, in progression to cancer, hundreds of genes are silenced or activated.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Although silencing of some genes in cancers occurs by mutation, a large proportion of carcinogenic gene silencing is a result of altered DNA methylation (see DNA methylation in cancer).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] DNA methylation causing silencing in cancer typically occurs at multiple CpG sites in the CpG islands that are present in the promoters of protein coding genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Altered expressions of microRNAs also silence or activate many genes in progression to cancer (see microRNAs in cancer).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Altered microRNA expression occurs through hyper/hypo-methylation of CpG sites in CpG islands in promoters controlling transcription of the microRNAs.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Silencing of DNA repair genes through methylation of CpG islands in their promoters appears to be especially important in progression to cancer (see methylation of DNA repair genes in cancer).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] The usage of the term canonical sequence to refer to a promoter is often problematic, and can lead to misunderstandings about promoter sequences.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Canonical implies perfect, in some sense.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In the case of a transcription factor binding site, there may be a single sequence that binds the protein most strongly under specified cellular conditions.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] However, natural selection may favor less energetic binding as a way of regulating transcriptional output.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] In this case, we may call the most common sequence in a population the wild-type sequence.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] It may not even be the most advantageous sequence to have under prevailing conditions.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Recent evidence also indicates that several genes (including the proto-oncogene c-myc) have G-quadruplex motifs as potential regulatory signals.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Some cases of many genetic diseases are associated with variations in promoters or transcription factors.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Some promoters are called constitutive as they are active in all circumstances in the cell, while others are regulated, becoming active in the cell only in response to specific stimuli.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] A tissue-specific promoter is a promoter that has activity in only certain cell types.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] When referring to a promoter some authors actually mean promoter + operator; i.e., the lac promoter is IPTG inducible, meaning that besides the lac promoter, the lac operon is also present.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] If the lac operator were not present the IPTG would not have an inducible effect.
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Another example is the Tac-Promoter system (Ptac).
[src:genetic-circuits/promoter-genetics] Notice how tac is written as a tac promoter, while in fact tac is actually both a promoter and an operator.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The **repressilator** is a genetic regulatory network consisting of at least one feedback loop with at least three genes, each expressing a protein that represses the next gene in the loop.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In biological research, repressilators have been used to build cellular models and understand cell function.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] There are both artificial and naturally occurring repressilators.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Recently, the naturally occurring repressilator clock gene circuit in *Arabidopsis thaliana* (*A. thaliana*) and mammalian systems have been studied.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Artificial repressilators were first engineered by Michael Elowitz and Stanislas Leibler in 2000, complementing other research projects studying simple systems of cell components and function.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In order to understand and model the design and cellular mechanisms that confers a cell's function, Elowitz and Leibler created an artificial network consisting of a loop with three transcriptional repressors.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] This network was designed from scratch to exhibit a stable oscillation that acts like an electrical oscillator system with fixed time periods.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The network was implemented in *Escherichia coli* (*E. coli)* via recombinant DNA transfer.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] It was then verified that the engineered colonies did indeed exhibit the desired oscillatory behavior.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The repressilator consists of three genes connected in a feedback loop, such that each gene represses the next gene in the loop and is repressed by the previous gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In the synthetic insertion into *E. coli*, green fluorescent protein (GFP) was used as a reporter so that the behavior of the network could be observed using fluorescence microscopy.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The design of the repressilator was guided by biological and circuit principles with discrete and stochastic models of analysis.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Six differential equations were used to model the kinetics of the repressilator system based on protein and mRNA concentrations, as well as appropriate parameter and Hill coefficient values.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In the study, Elowitz and Leibler generated figures showing oscillations of repressor proteins, using integration and typical parameter values as well as a stochastic version of the repressilator model using similar parameters.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] These models were analyzed to determine the values of various rates that would yield a sustained oscillation.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] It was found that these oscillations were favored by promoters coupled to efficient ribosome binding sites, cooperative transcriptional repressors, and comparable protein and mRNA decay rates.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] This analysis motivated two design features which were engineered into the genes.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] First, promoter regions were replaced with a more efficient hybrid promoter which combined the *E. coli* phage lambda PL (λ PL) promoter with *lac repressor* (*Lacl*) and *Tet repressor* (*TetR*) operator sequences.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Second, to reduce the disparity between the lifetimes of the repressor proteins and the mRNAs, a carboxy terminal tag based on the ssrA-RNA sequence was added at the 3' end of each repressor gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] This tag is recognized by proteases which target the protein for degradation.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The design was implemented using a low-copy plasmid encoding the repressilator and a higher-copy reporter, which were used to transform a culture of *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Circadian circuits in plants feature a transcriptional regulatory feedback loop called the repressilator.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In the core oscillator loop (outlined in gray) in *A. thaliana*, light is first sensed by two cryptochromes and five phytochromes.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Two transcription factors, Circadian Clock Associated 1 (CCA1) and Late Elongated Hypocotyl (LHY), repress genes associated with evening expression like *Timing of CAB expression 1* (*TOC1*) and activate genes associated with morning expression by binding to their promoters.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] *TOC1*, an evening gene, positively regulates *CCA1* and *LHY* via an unknown mechanism.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Evening-phased transcription factor CCA1 Hiking Expedition (CHE) and histone demethylase jumonji C domain-containing 5 (JMJD5) directly repress *CCA1*.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Other components have been found to be expressed throughout the day and either directly or indirectly inhibit or activate a consequent element in the circadian circuit, thereby creating a complex, robust and flexible network of feedback loops.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The morning-phase expression loop refers to the genes and proteins that regulate rhythms during the day in *A. thaliana*.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The two main genes are LHY and CCA1, which encode LHY and CCA1 transcription factors.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] These proteins form heterodimers that enter the nucleus and bind to the *TOC1* gene promoter, repressing the production of TOC1 protein.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] When TOC1 protein is expressed, it serves to regulate *LHY* and *CCA1* by inhibition of their transcription.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Alexandra Pokhilo, who used computational analyses to show that TOC1 served this role as an inhibitor of *LHY* and *CCA1* expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The morning loop serves to inhibit hypocotyl elongation, in contrast with the evening-phase loop which promotes hypocotyl elongation.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The morning phase loop has shown to be incapable of supporting circadian oscillation when evening-phase expression genes have been mutated, suggesting the interdependency of each component in this naturally occurring repressilator.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Mammals evolved an endogenous timing mechanism to coordinate both physiology and behavior to the 24 hour period.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In 2016, researchers identified a sequence of three subsequent inhibitions within this mechanism that they identified as a repressilator, which is now believed to serve as a major core element of this circadian network.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The necessity of this system was established through a series of gene knockouts amongst *cryptochrome* (*Cry*), *period* (*Per*), and *Rev-erb* *--* core mammalian clock genes whose knockouts lead to arrhythmicity.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The model that these researchers generated includes *Bmal1* as a driver of E-box mediated transcription, *Per2* and *Cry1* as early and late E-box repressors, respectively, as well as the D-box regulator Dbp and the nuclear receptor Rev-erb-α.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The sequential inhibitions by *Rev-erb*, *Per* and *Cry1* can generate sustained oscillations, and by clamping all other components except for this repressilator oscillations persisted with similar amplitudes and periods.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] All oscillating networks seem to involve any combination of these three core genes, as demonstrated in various schematics released by researchers.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The repressilator model has been used to model and study other biological pathways and systems.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Since, extensive work into the repressilator's modeling capacities has been performed.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In 2003, the repressilator's representation and validation of biological models, being a model with many variables, was performed using the Simpathica system, which verified that the model does indeed oscillate with all of its complexities.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] As stated in Elowitz and Leibler's original work, the ultimate goal for repressilator research is to build an artificial circadian clock that mirrors its natural, endogenous counterpart.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] This would involve developing an artificial clock with reduced noise and temperature compensation in order to better understand circadian rhythms that can be found in every domain of life.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Disruption of circadian rhythms may lead to loss of rhythmicity in metabolic and transcriptional processes, and even quicken the onset of certain neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's disease.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In 2017, oscillators that generated circadian rhythms and were not influenced much by temperature were created in a laboratory.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Pathologically, the repressilator model can be used to model cell growth and abnormalities that may arise, such as those present in cancer cells.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] In doing so, new treatments may be developed based on circadian activity of cancerous cells.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Additionally, in 2016, a research team improved upon the previous design of the repressilator.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Following noise (signal processing) analysis, the authors moved the GFP reporter construct onto the repressilator plasmid and removed the ssrA degradation tags from each repressor protein.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] This extended the period and improved the regularity of the oscillations of the repressilator.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Artificial repressilators were discovered by implanting a synthetic inhibition loop into *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] This represented the first implementation of synthetic oscillations into an organism.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Further implications of this include the possibility of rescuing mutated components of oscillations synthetically in model organisms.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The artificial repressilator is a milestone of synthetic biology which shows that genetic regulatory networks can be designed and implemented to perform novel functions.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] However, it was found that the cells' oscillations drifted out of phase after a period of time and the artificial repressilator's activity was influenced by cell growth.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] The initial experiment therefore gave new appreciation to the circadian clock found in many organisms, as endogenous repressilators are significantly more robust than implanted artificial repressilators.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] New investigations at the RIKEN Quantitative Biology Center have found that chemical modifications to a single protein molecule could form a temperature independent, self-sustainable oscillator .
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] Artificial repressilators could potentially aid research and treatments in fields ranging from circadian biology to endocrinology.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] They are increasingly able to demonstrate the synchronization inherent to natural biological systems and the factors that affect them.
[src:genetic-circuits/repressilator] A better understanding of the naturally occurring repressilator in model organisms with endogenous, circadian timings, like *A. thaliana,* has applications in agriculture, especially in regards to plant rearing and livestock management.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] In molecular biology, a **riboswitch** is a regulatory segment of a messenger RNA molecule that binds a small molecule, resulting in a change in production of the proteins encoded by the mRNA.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Thus, an mRNA that contains a riboswitch is directly involved in regulating its own activity, in response to the concentrations of its effector molecule.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The discovery that modern organisms use RNA to bind small molecules, and discriminate against closely related analogs, expanded the known natural capabilities of RNA beyond its ability to code for proteins, catalyze reactions, or to bind other RNA or protein macromolecules.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The original definition of the term "riboswitch" specified that they directly sense small-molecule metabolite concentrations.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Although this definition remains in common use, some biologists have used a broader definition that includes other cis-regulatory RNAs.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] However, this article will discuss only metabolite-binding riboswitches.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Most known riboswitches occur in bacteria, but functional riboswitches of one type (the TPP riboswitch) have been discovered in archaea, plants and certain fungi.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] TPP riboswitches have also been predicted in archaea, but have not been experimentally tested.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Prior to the discovery of riboswitches, the mechanism by which some genes involved in multiple metabolic pathways were regulated remained mysterious.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Accumulating evidence increasingly suggested the then-unprecedented idea that the mRNAs involved might bind metabolites directly, to affect their own regulation.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] These data included conserved RNA secondary structures often found in the untranslated regions (UTRs) of the relevant genes and the success of procedures to create artificial small molecule-binding RNAs called aptamers.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] In 2002, the first comprehensive proofs of multiple classes of riboswitches were published, including protein-free binding assays, and metabolite-binding riboswitches were established as a new mechanism of gene regulation.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Many of the earliest riboswitches to be discovered corresponded to conserved sequence "motifs" (patterns) in 5' UTRs that appeared to correspond to a structured RNA.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Bioinformatics has played a role in more recent discoveries, with increasing automation of the basic comparative genomics strategy.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Barrick *et al.* (2004) used BLAST to find UTRs homologous to all UTRs in *Bacillus subtilis*.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Some of these homologous sets were inspected for conserved structure, resulting in 10 RNA-like motifs.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Three of these were later experimentally confirmed as the glmS, glycine and PreQ1-I riboswitches (see below).
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Subsequent comparative genomics efforts using additional taxa of bacteria and improved computer algorithms have identified further riboswitches that are experimentally confirmed, as well as conserved RNA structures that are hypothesized to function as riboswitches.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Riboswitches are often conceptually divided into two parts: an aptamer and an expression platform.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The aptamer directly binds the small molecule, and the expression platform undergoes structural changes in response to the changes in the aptamer.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The expression platform is what regulates gene expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Expression platforms typically turn off gene expression in response to the small molecule, but some turn it on.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The following riboswitch mechanisms have been experimentally demonstrated.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The following is a list of experimentally validated riboswitches, organized by ligand.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Candidate metabolite-binding riboswitches have been identified using bioinformatics, and have moderately complex secondary structures and several highly conserved nucleotide positions, as these features are typical of riboswitches that must specifically bind a small molecule.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Riboswitch candidates are also consistently located in the 5' UTRs of protein-coding genes, and these genes are suggestive of metabolite binding, as these are also features of most known riboswitches.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Hypothesized riboswitch candidates highly consistent with the preceding criteria are as follows: crcB RNA Motif, manA RNA motif, pfl RNA motif, ydaO/yuaA leader, yjdF RNA motif, ykkC-yxkD leader (and related ykkC-III RNA motif) and the yybP-ykoY leader.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The functions of these hypothetical riboswitches remain unknown.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Riboswitches have been also investigated using in-silico approaches.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] The SwiSpot tool somehow covers both the groups, as it uses conformational predictions to assess the presence of riboswitches.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Other computational investigations look into the druggability properties of riboswitch binding sites, assessing their potency as potential novel drug targets.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Additionally, generative models such as restricted Boltzmann machines have been applied to learn sequence dependencies and design *de novo* functional RNA riboswitches.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Riboswitches demonstrate that naturally occurring RNA can bind small molecules specifically, a capability that many previously believed was the domain of proteins or artificially constructed RNAs called aptamers.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] It has been suggested that some riboswitches might represent ancient regulatory systems, or even remnants of RNA-world ribozymes whose bindings domains are conserved.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Indeed, some antibiotics whose mechanism of action was unknown for decades have been shown to operate by targeting riboswitches.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] For example, when the antibiotic pyrithiamine enters the cell, it is metabolized into pyrithiamine pyrophosphate.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Pyrithiamine pyrophosphate has been shown to bind and activate the TPP riboswitch, causing the cell to cease the synthesis and import of TPP.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Because pyrithiamine pyrophosphate does not substitute for TPP as a coenzyme, the cell dies.
[src:genetic-circuits/riboswitch] Since riboswitches are an effective method of controlling gene expression in natural organisms, there has been interest in engineering artificial riboswitches for industrial and medical applications such as gene therapy.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] The goal of synthetic biology is to generate an array of tunable and characterized parts, or modules, with which any desirable synthetic biological circuit can be easily designed and implemented.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] These circuits can serve as a method to modify cellular functions, create cellular responses to environmental conditions, or influence cellular development.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] By implementing rational, controllable logic elements in cellular systems, researchers can use living systems as engineered "biological machines" to perform a vast range of useful functions.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] The first natural gene circuit studied in detail was the lac operon.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] In studies of diauxic growth of *E. coli* on two-sugar media, Jacques Monod and Francois Jacob discovered that *E.coli* preferentially consumes the more easily processed glucose before switching to lactose metabolism.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] They discovered that the mechanism that controlled the metabolic "switching" function was a two-part control mechanism on the lac operon.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] When lactose is present in the cell the enzyme β-galactosidase is produced to convert lactose into glucose or galactose.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] When lactose is absent in the cell the lac repressor inhibits the production of the enzyme β-galactosidase to prevent any inefficient processes within the cell.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] The lac operon is used in the biotechnology industry for production of recombinant proteins for therapeutic use.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] The gene or genes for producing an exogenous protein are placed on a plasmid under the control of the lac promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Initially the cells are grown in a medium that does not contain lactose or other sugars, so the new genes are not expressed.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Once the cells reach a certain point in their growth, isopropyl β-D-1-thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG) is added.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] IPTG, a molecule similar to lactose, but with a sulfur bond that is not hydrolyzable so that E. coli does not digest it, is used to activate or "induce" the production of the new protein.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Once the cells are induced, it is difficult to remove IPTG from the cells and therefore it is difficult to stop expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Two early examples of synthetic biological circuits were published in Nature in 2000.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] One, by Tim Gardner, Charles Cantor, and Jim Collins working at Boston University, demonstrated a "bistable" switch in *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] The switch is turned on by heating the culture of bacteria and turned off by addition of IPTG.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] They used green fluorescent protein as a reporter for their system.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Currently, synthetic circuits are a burgeoning area of research in systems biology with more publications detailing synthetic biological circuits published every year.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Both immediate and long term applications exist for the use of synthetic biological circuits, including different applications for metabolic engineering, and synthetic biology.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Those demonstrated successfully include pharmaceutical production, and fuel production.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] However, methods involving direct genetic introduction are not inherently effective without invoking the basic principles of synthetic cellular circuits.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] For example, each of these successful systems employs a method to introduce all-or-none induction or expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] This is a biological circuit where a simple repressor or promoter is introduced to facilitate creation of the product, or inhibition of a competing pathway.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] However, with the limited understanding of cellular networks and natural circuitry, implementation of more robust schemes with more precise control and feedback is hindered.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Therein lies the immediate interest in synthetic cellular circuits.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Development in understanding cellular circuitry can lead to exciting new modifications, such as cells which can respond to environmental stimuli.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] For example, cells could be developed that signal toxic surroundings and react by activating pathways used to degrade the perceived toxin.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] To develop such a cell, it is necessary to create a complex synthetic cellular circuit which can respond appropriately to a given stimulus.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Given synthetic cellular circuits represent a form of control for cellular activities, it can be reasoned that with complete understanding of cellular pathways, "plug and play" cells with well defined genetic circuitry can be engineered.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] It is widely believed that if a proper toolbox of parts is generated, synthetic cells can be developed implementing only the pathways necessary for cell survival and reproduction.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] From this cell, to be thought of as a minimal genome cell, one can add pieces from the toolbox to create a well defined pathway with appropriate synthetic circuitry for an effective feedback system.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Because of the basic ground up construction method, and the proposed database of mapped circuitry pieces, techniques mirroring those used to model computer or electronic circuits can be used to redesign cells and model cells for easy troubleshooting and predictive behavior and yields.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Elowitz et al. and Fung et al. created oscillatory circuits that use multiple self-regulating mechanisms to create a time-dependent oscillation of gene product expression.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Gardner et al. used mutual repression between two control units to create an implementation of a toggle switch capable of controlling cells in a bistable manner: transient stimuli resulting in persistent responses.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Gene regulation is an essential part of developmental processes.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] During development, genes are turned on and off in different tissues, changes in regulatory mechanisms may result in genetic switching in a bistable system, the gene switches serve as regulatory molecule binding sites.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] These are proteins that activate transcription when they land on a gene switch and thereby express the gene that was expected to operate as a memory device, allowing cell fate decisions to be chosen and maintained.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Toggle switch which operates using two mutually inhibitory genes, each promoter is inhibited by the repressor that is transcribed by the opposing promoter.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Toggle switch design: Inducer 1 inactivates repressor 1, which means repressor 2 is produced.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Repressor 2, in turn, stops transcription of the repressor 1 gene and the reporter gene.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Using negative feedback and identical promoters, linearizer gene circuits can impose uniform gene expression that depends linearly on extracellular chemical inducer concentration.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Synthetic gene circuits can control gene expression heterogeneity can be controlled independently of the gene expression mean.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Engineered systems are the result of implementation of combinations of different control mechanisms.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] A limited counting mechanism was implemented by a pulse-controlled gene cascade and application of logic elements enables genetic "programming" of cells as in the research of Tabor et al., which synthesized a photosensitive bacterial edge detection program.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Recent developments in artificial gene synthesis and the corresponding increase in competition within the industry have led to a significant drop in price and wait time of gene synthesis and helped improve methods used in circuit design.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] At the moment, circuit design is improving at a slow pace because of insufficient organization of known multiple gene interactions and mathematical models.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] This issue is being addressed by applying computer-aided design (CAD) software to provide multimedia representations of circuits through images, text and programming language applied to biological circuits.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Some of the more well known CAD programs include GenoCAD, Clotho framework and j5.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] GenoCAD uses grammars, which are either opensource or user generated "rules" which include the available genes and known gene interactions for cloning organisms.
[src:genetic-circuits/synthetic-biological-circuit] Clotho framework uses the Biobrick standard rules.
